{
  "text": "We say that the set of points {x j } r j=1 \u2282 R n has the MNI-property (minimal non-interpolation property) with respect to the {a i } m i=1 , if {x j } r j=1 has the NI-property and no proper subset of the {x j } r j=1 has the NI-property. The following result, to be found in Braess, Pinkus [CITATION_1] , easily follows from the above definitions.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "119945051"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "119945051": {
      "title": "Interpolation by ridge functions",
      "abstract": "Abstract We consider the problem of interpolation by linear combinations of ridge functions. A ridge function is a function of the form \u0192( a \u00b7 x ) where \u0192: R \u2192 R , a \u2208 R d \\{ 0 } is a fixed vector, and x \u2208 R d is the variable. The solvability of the interpolation problem is characterized by geometric properties."
    }
  }
}